 Let the total number of pennies in Joyce's bank be represented by {eq}x{/eq}.


At first, she counts them by fives, so we have  
\begin{align*}
x & \equiv 1 \pmod{5}\\
\end{align*} 
At the same time, she also counts them by threes, so 
\begin{align*}
x & \equiv 2 \pmod{3}\\
\end{align*} 
The problem gives us the following figure:

By Fermat's Little Theorem, if  \begin{align*} a & \equiv b \pmod{p},\\ \end{align*} and \begin{align*} p & \nmid a,\\ \end{align*} then {eq}a^{p-1} \equiv b^{p-1} \pmod{p}.\\ {/eq}
Since we know that 5 is prime and coprime to 3 because 5 does not divide 3, our problem becomes trivial.
Observation at first glance does not tell us much, but we have  2 congruence pairs, and the modulus is relatively small and the product of the two modulo numbers are 15, which is less than 49(cumulative total of pennies after 7 cycles). We can now easily figure out the  possibilities of  $$x\equiv 1 (mod5) $$, $$x \equiv  2(mod 3)$$ by the testyly random method with the multiples of 2 that match 1(mod 5) and 3 and then missing the rest of the congruence pairs binaries. 
Only 22 should be choosen, and that should be our answer (the possible answers are: 17,22,27 and 32, removed 17 and 27 and 32 because they have extra pennies).]<answer> 22 </answer>

